## 1. Recent Changes Review (Last 2 Commits)

The last two commits (`3272c41`, `ed40841`) modify journal matching:

### ✅ What's Good
- Expanded `ABBREV_MAP` from 22 to 68 abbreviation entries — solid coverage improvement
- Pre-tokenized DB journals to avoid millions of redundant regex executions — good optimization
- Changed arrow `→` to ASCII [to](file:///c:/Users/public.LAPTOP-17PSCTIQ/Desktop/MATHIMATA/proxorimena/project/etl/06_match_journals.py#148-150) in print statements — portability fix

### ⚠️ Concerns

> [!WARNING]
> **Overlap threshold lowered from 0.55 to 0.40** — This is aggressive. At 40%, a journal with 3 meaningful tokens only needs ~1.2 matching tokens to qualify. This **will produce false-positive matches** for journals with short or generic names (e.g., "Systems", "Networks", "Logic").

**Recommendation:**  
- Add a **minimum token count guard**: if either journal name has ≤ 2 tokens, require a higher threshold (e.g., 0.70)
- Log the top 20 closest "near-miss" matches so you can verify quality manually
- Consider a `confidence` column with `high/medium/low` labels to flag risky matches

### 🐛 Bug: `stat` abbreviation

```python
r'\bstat\.?\b': 'statistics',
```

This maps **all** occurrences of "stat" → "statistics", but in many contexts "stat" means "statistical" (e.g., "Stat. Comput." = "Statistical Computing", not "Statistics Computing"). This was noted in commit `3272c41` — the fix is partial. The regex `\bstat\b` without a dot will also match the standalone word, which may be correct, but should be audited.

