## 5. ETL Pipeline Review

### ✅ Strengths
- Well-ordered 9-step pipeline with clear naming
- Schema uses proper InnoDB with FKs and CHECK constraints
- Handling of N:M author relationships with `author_order`
- Backup script provided
- Performance indexes created separately ([09_performance_optimization.sql](file:///c:/Users/public.LAPTOP-17PSCTIQ/Desktop/MATHIMATA/proxorimena/project/etl/09_performance_optimization.sql), [09_search_indexes.sql](file:///c:/Users/public.LAPTOP-17PSCTIQ/Desktop/MATHIMATA/proxorimena/project/etl/09_search_indexes.sql))

### ⚠️ Issues

| Issue | Severity |
|---|---|
| [etl/config.py](file:///c:/Users/public.LAPTOP-17PSCTIQ/Desktop/MATHIMATA/proxorimena/project/etl/config.py) likely has hardcoded DB credentials (same as [backend/config.py](file:///c:/Users/public.LAPTOP-17PSCTIQ/Desktop/MATHIMATA/proxorimena/project/backend/config.py) but separate file — DRY violation). Should share or use `.env`. | 🟡 Medium |
| The 0.40 overlap threshold risks false-positive journal matches (see Section 1) | 🟡 Medium |
| No validation step after loading (e.g., row count assertions, FK integrity check) | 🟡 Medium |
| [07_load_papers.py](file:///c:/Users/public.LAPTOP-17PSCTIQ/Desktop/MATHIMATA/proxorimena/project/etl/07_load_papers.py) takes ~35 mins — could be parallelized or use `LOAD DATA INFILE` for speed | 🟢 Low |

